Intersection of two linked lists

Problem

Given two linked lists, find the node at which they intersect (if they do).

Example

First approach

Hint

Expand

\(\text{length first} - \text{length second}\)

Solution

Explanation

Implementation

fun getIntersectionNode(headA: ListNode?, headB: ListNode?): ListNode? {
  var cursorA = headA
  var cursorB = headB
  var diff = headA.length - headB.length

  while (diff > 0) {
    cursorA = cursorA!!.next
    diff--
  }
  while (diff < 0) {
    cursorB = cursorB!!.next
    diff++
  }

  while (cursorA != cursorB) {
    cursorA = cursorA!!.next
    cursorB = cursorB!!.next
  }

  return cursorA
}

val ListNode?.length: Int
  get() {
    var l = 0
    var c = this
    while (c != null) {
      l++
      c = c.next
    }
    return l
  }

Complexity

Expand

We need to traverse both linked lists first to find their lengths, that's \(a+b\) steps. Next we need to traverse \(min(a, b)\) steps to find the common node or null if there is none. So that's \(a + b + min(a, b) \approx O(a+b)\).

Second approach

Hint

Expand

Don't worry about memory

fun getIntersectionNode(headA: ListNode?, headB: ListNode?): ListNode? {
  val seen = HashSet<ListNode>()

  var cursor = headA
  while (cursor != null) {
    seen.add(cursor)
    cursor = cursor.next
  }

  cursor = headB
  while (cursor != null) {
    if (cursor in seen) return cursor
    cursor = cursor.next
  }

  return null
}

Complexity

Expand

We need to traverse either of the list to add all the nodes to the set. Since we don't know the lengths ahead of time, that's \(max(a, b)\) steps. Followed by \(min(a, b)\) steps in the other list to find the common node or reach null. That's \(max(a, b) + min(a, b) = a + b \approx O(a+b)\) steps, and \(O(max(a, b))\) memory.

Third approach

Hint

Expand

Move around the cursors between the two lists.

Solution

Example

Explanation

First note that in a linked list of length \(L\) there are \(L-1\) links, and a cursor starting at the head will reach null after \(L\) steps.

Now let's say we have first linked list of length \(a\) and second of length \(b\). We start two cursors \(c_1\) and \(c_2\) at the head of each list respectively.

Steps \(c_1\) position \(c_2\) position Notes
\(0\) \(a\) steps from being null \(b\) steps from being null
\(b\) \(a-b\) steps from being null is null
\(1\) \(a-b-1\) steps from being null \(a\) steps from being null Since \(c_2\) is null, moved it to front of first linked list
\(a-b-1\) is null \(a - (a-b-1) = b+1\) steps from being null
\(1\) \(b\) steps from being null \(b\) steps from being null Since \(c_1\) is null, moved it to front of second linked list

At the end of this, both cursors are \(b\) steps away from being null and we can move them in sync until either we reach the end of linked lists or find a common node.

Implementation

fun getIntersectionNode(headA: ListNode?, headB: ListNode?): ListNode? {
  var x = headA
  var y = headB

  while (x != y) {
    x = if (x == null) headB else x.next
    y = if (y == null) headA else y.next
  }

  return x
}

Complexity

Expand

The table above shows that we need \(0 + b + 1 + (a-b-1) + 1 = a + 1\) steps before both cursors are same distance away from the end (given \(a > b\)), that's \(max(a, b) + 1\) steps. Followed by \(min(a, b)\) steps to find the common node or null. This gives the time complexity of \(max(a, b) + 1 + min(a, b) = a + b + 1 \approx O(a+b)\) steps.

@Test
fun example_1() {
  val l1 = ListNode(4)
  l1.next = ListNode(1)
  l1.next!!.next = ListNode(8)
  l1.next!!.next!!.next = ListNode(4)
  l1.next!!.next!!.next!!.next = ListNode(5)

  val l2 = ListNode(5)
  l2.next = ListNode(6)
  l2.next!!.next = ListNode(1)
  l2.next!!.next!!.next = l1.next!!.next

  assertThat(getIntersectionNode(l1, l2)).isEqualTo(l1.next!!.next)
}

@Test
fun example_2() {
  val l1 = ListNode(1)
  l1.next = ListNode(9)
  l1.next!!.next = ListNode(1)
  l1.next!!.next!!.next = ListNode(2)
  l1.next!!.next!!.next!!.next = ListNode(4)

  val l2 = ListNode(3)
  l2.next = l1.next!!.next!!.next

  assertThat(getIntersectionNode(l1, l2)).isEqualTo(l1.next!!.next!!.next)
}

@Test
fun example_3() {
  val l1 = ListNode(2)
  l1.next = ListNode(6)
  l1.next!!.next = ListNode(4)

  val l2 = ListNode(1)
  l2.next = ListNode(5)

  assertThat(getIntersectionNode(l1, l2)).isEqualTo(null)
}
